The year 1691 marked a pivotal, if somewhat uninspired, moment in the administrative partitioning of the colony. [Lower Norfolk County](/Lower_Norfolk_County), itself a product of earlier divisions, was once again deemed too cumbersome, too expansive, or perhaps simply too inconvenient. It was subsequently bisected, giving rise to two new entities: [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia) and [Princess Anne County](/Princess_Anne_County,_Virginia). This was, of course, presented as a measure to 'accommodate settlement,' which is to say, to better manage the ever-increasing human footprint and its associated paperwork.

The rather straightforward naming of [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia) is attributed to Captain [Adam Thoroughgood](/Adam_Thoroughgood) (1604–1640), a figure of some prominence in the early colonial days. Like countless others who sought opportunity, or perhaps merely escape, he had journeyed from England to [Virginia](/Virginia). In a move that demonstrated either deep nostalgia or a profound lack of imagination, he chose to name this new colonial division after his original 'home' county across the vast expanse of the Atlantic Ocean. One can only imagine the profound sense of originality that must have permeated the colonial council chambers that day. &#91;4&#93;

Following its official establishment in 1691, [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia) managed to retain a semblance of its original form for a surprisingly long stretch, enduring for over two centuries. During this period, [Portsmouth](/Portsmouth,_Virginia) emerged as the primary [county seat](/County_seat) and, alongside the burgeoning city of [Norfolk](/Norfolk,_Virginia), solidified its position as a significant center of commerce and activity. Smaller, nascent communities also began to coalesce, notably at [Berkley](/Berkley,_Virginia) and the area that would later become [South Norfolk](/South_Norfolk,_Virginia). However, the relative stability was merely a prelude to the inevitable. In 1871, both [Portsmouth](/Portsmouth,_Virginia) and [Norfolk](/Norfolk,_Virginia) embarked upon a path of municipal independence, a peculiar jurisdictional status unique to [Virginia](/Virginia) that allowed them to separate entirely from their parent county. Despite this severance, [Portsmouth](/Portsmouth,_Virginia) inexplicably retained its role as the [county seat](/County_seat) for a time, a bureaucratic anomaly. Not to be outdone, [South Norfolk](/South_Norfolk,_Virginia) followed suit, achieving its own independent city status in 1919.

The subsequent decades proved to be a period of relentless attrition for [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia), as its territory was systematically devoured. The [incorporated town](/Incorporated_town) of [Berkley](/Berkley,_Virginia), which had once been a part of the county's fabric, was swallowed whole by [Norfolk](/Norfolk,_Virginia). The scenic areas of [Sewell's Point](/Sewell%27s_Point), the distinctive landform of [Willoughby Spit](/Willoughby_Spit), and the popular recreational spot of [Ocean View](/Ocean_View,_Virginia) were similarly annexed, one after another, by the ever-expanding city of [Norfolk](/Norfolk,_Virginia). By 1960, the situation had become rather dire: virtually the entire expanse of [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia) situated on the eastern bank of the [Elizabeth River](/Elizabeth_River_(Virginia)) and lying north of the then-prominent Virginia Beach Boulevard had been absorbed by various neighboring jurisdictions. The western flank fared no better, with West Norfolk (often referred to as Churchland) being ceded to [Portsmouth](/Portsmouth,_Virginia), and even the comparatively junior [South Norfolk](/South_Norfolk,_Virginia) managing to annex a substantial portion of the county's remaining land. It was less a county and more a collection of shrinking fragments, clinging to a fading identity.

### 1963: Creating a new city, Chesapeake

While the administrative boundaries of [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia) were in constant flux, the political leanings of its residents, as reflected in the [United States presidential election results for Norfolk County, Virginia](/United_States_presidential_election_results_for_Norfolk_County,_Virginia), presented their own fascinating, if ultimately irrelevant, patterns. For much of the late 19th century, the county showed a clear preference for the [Republican Party](/Republican_Party_(United_States)), a trend that diverged significantly in the early 20th century, shifting decidedly towards the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)), particularly from [1904](/1904_United_States_presidential_election_in_Virginia) through [1924](/1924_United_States_presidential_election_in_Virginia). This Democratic dominance, punctuated only by a brief Republican resurgence in [1928](/1928_United_States_presidential_election_in_Virginia), largely persisted until the county's dissolution, reflecting broader regional and national political currents, and perhaps, the evolving demographics of a shrinking, yet still diverse, population. One might observe that, much like its physical territory, the political landscape of [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia) was rarely static, a testament to the fickle nature of human allegiance. (References for election results: [5], [6])

