The peculiar legal landscape of [Virginia](/Virginia) dictates that its independent cities are, by statute, entirely immune from annexation by one another. This rather convenient legislative quirk set the stage for the final, desperate maneuver that would seal [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia)'s fate. In the early 1960s, the [City of Norfolk](/Norfolk,_Virginia), ever ambitious, launched its most recent attempt to absorb yet another fragment of the dwindling [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia). This aggressive expansion threatened to achieve a rather complete encirclement of the already diminutive [City of South Norfolk](/South_Norfolk,_Virginia). Such a successful, if rather predatory, annexation would have undeniably jeopardized [South Norfolk](/South_Norfolk,_Virginia)'s very existence and viability as an independent municipal entity. Faced with this existential threat, and with the residents of the remaining [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia) harboring their own well-founded anxieties about future annexation suits, an unlikely alliance was forged. In this protracted, rather petty 'battle of municipalities,' the beleaguered residents of [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia) and the threatened [City of South Norfolk](/South_Norfolk,_Virginia) found common cause, uniting against the perceived territorial ambitions of [Norfolk](/Norfolk,_Virginia) proper.

A precedent for their predicament, and indeed a viable solution, had been established approximately a decade prior. The successful consolidation strategy employed by [Elizabeth City County](/Elizabeth_City_County,_Virginia), the [Town of Phoebus](/Phoebus,_Virginia), and the [City of Hampton](/Hampton,_Virginia) provided a blueprint for escape. Thus, in 1963, after the requisite referendums were held among the voters of both [South Norfolk](/South_Norfolk,_Virginia) and what little remained of [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia), and with the final rubber stamp of approval from the ever-deliberate [Virginia General Assembly](/Virginia_General_Assembly), a decision was reached. [South Norfolk](/South_Norfolk,_Virginia) and nearly all the remaining territory of [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia) consolidated. They reorganized not as a larger county, but as an entirely new independent city: the [City of Chesapeake](/Chesapeake,_Virginia). The name, of course, was chosen by the voters, a final act of self-determination, or perhaps, a resigned acceptance of a new, sprawling identity. And so, [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia) ceased to be, its fragmented legacy absorbed into a new, often contradictory, municipal whole.

